&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 3)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the given sentence, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;article &amp;#39;a&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;used before&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;President&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;incorrect&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct article should be&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;the&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;because&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;both titles refer to specific individuals&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Prime Minister&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;the President&lt;/strong&gt; are visiting the town.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;article &amp;#39;the&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;should be used&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;in place of&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;article &amp;#39;a&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;before &amp;#39;President&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Hence, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;option 3&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Correct sentence:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;The Prime Minister and&lt;u&gt; the President &lt;/u&gt;are visiting the town today to see the preparations for the International Seminar&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;C&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;attack&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; is used as &lt;strong&gt;a verb and is followed by its object&lt;/strong&gt;, it &lt;strong&gt;doesn&amp;#39;t take any preposition with it&lt;/strong&gt;.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;Ex: The man &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;attacked him/&lt;s&gt;on him&lt;/s&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt; with a knife&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the given sentence, &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;attacked (past participle or V3 of &amp;#39;attack&amp;#39;)&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; is used and&lt;strong&gt; immediately followed by the person attacked&lt;/strong&gt;. Therefore, the use of preposition &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;on&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39; is &lt;strong&gt;incorrect&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It&amp;#39;s clear part &lt;strong&gt;C&lt;/strong&gt; of the given sentence contains an error.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Therefore, the &lt;strong&gt;correct &lt;/strong&gt;answer is &lt;strong&gt;option 1)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct sentence&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;: &lt;em&gt;That Brutus, who was his trusted friend had attacked &lt;strong&gt;&lt;s&gt;on&lt;/s&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; him causing&amp;nbsp;heart break to Julius Caesa&lt;/em&gt;r.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option (3) i.e. (c) &lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;an animal is called sharing&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); font-size: var(--bs-body-font-size); font-weight: var(--bs-body-font-weight); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The process of removing wool from the body of an animal is referred to as &amp;quot;shearing,&amp;quot; not &amp;quot;sharing&amp;quot;. So, the correct phrasing should be: &amp;#39;an animal is called shearing.&amp;#39;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;Sharing&amp;quot; denotes the act of giving a portion of something to others, which is irrelevant in the given context.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Here, the phrase &amp;quot;is called sharing&amp;quot; should be corrected to &amp;quot;is called shearing&amp;quot; to show the actual process of removing wool from an animal&amp;#39;s body.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the incorrect term &amp;quot;sharing&amp;quot; serves as a grammatical error, distorting the meaning of the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, the correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;has won&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The segment that contains a &lt;strong&gt;grammatical error is &amp;quot;has won&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;subject of the sentence is &amp;quot;Both Reeta and Ronika&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;, which is a &lt;strong&gt;plural subject.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus, the &lt;strong&gt;verb should also be plural. &lt;/strong&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;correct verb form would be &amp;quot;have won&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Example: &lt;em&gt;John and Mary have won the game&lt;/em&gt;.
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;In this sentence, &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;John and Mary&amp;quot; is the plural subject,&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;have won&amp;quot; is the correct verb&lt;/strong&gt; form to agree with the subject.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Example: &lt;em&gt;He and she has gone to the store.&lt;/em&gt;
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;In this sentence,&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;He and she&amp;quot; is the subject,&lt;/strong&gt; and &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;has gone&amp;quot; is the incorrect verb&lt;/strong&gt; form because the &lt;strong&gt;subject is plural. &lt;/strong&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;correct form would be &amp;quot;have gone&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence, the &lt;strong&gt;correct&amp;nbsp;sentence&lt;/strong&gt; would be&amp;nbsp;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Both Reeta and Ronika have won the dance competition this year&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; as&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;have won&amp;quot; correctly agrees with the plural subject &amp;quot;Both Reeta and Ronika&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;verb and its subject must match up in number &lt;/strong&gt;according to English grammar. Thus, if the&lt;strong&gt; subject is singular, the verb must also be singular, &lt;/strong&gt;and if the&lt;strong&gt; subject is plural, the verb must also be plural.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Example: Having a &lt;strong&gt;singular verb and a singular subject&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;The dog barks at the strange man&lt;/em&gt;.
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;singular verb that agrees with the subject&lt;/strong&gt; in this sentence is &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;barks,&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; and the &lt;strong&gt;singular subject&lt;/strong&gt; in this sentence is &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;dog.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Example: &lt;strong&gt;Plural subjects and plural verbs&lt;/strong&gt;:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;The dogs bark at the strange man&lt;/em&gt;.
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Dogs&amp;quot; is the plural subject&lt;/strong&gt; in this sentence, and &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;bark&amp;quot; is the verb that agrees with the subject in the plural.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;No error&amp;#39; (Option 4).&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The sentence &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;I would never apologize if I were you&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; correctly uses the second conditional mood, which is used to talk about hypothetical or unlikely situations.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The phrase &amp;quot;I would&amp;quot; (Option 1) is a properly used conditional modal verb phrase for a hypothetical situation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The dependent clause &amp;quot;never apologize if&amp;quot; (Option 2) correctly introduces the hypothetical criteria that would trigger the scenario.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The subjective mood phrase &amp;quot;I were you&amp;quot; (Option 3) is grammatically correct, as &amp;quot;were&amp;quot; is used instead of &amp;quot;was&amp;quot; after &amp;quot;if&amp;quot; when the speaker is making a supposition or hypothetical statement.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Consequently, there is no error in this sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is Option 4.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&#039;2&#039;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;i.e.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;consequency, we had&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;The word &lt;strong&gt;&quot;consequency&quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is incorrect in the given sentence. The correct word should be &lt;strong&gt;&quot;consequently.&quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&quot;Consequently&quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is an adverb used to mean &quot;as a result&quot; or &quot;therefore,&quot; and fits the intended meaning of the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;The rest of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not contain any errors.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Correct sentence:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;The project was delayed because of unforeseen issues; consequently, we had to adjust our timeline.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Usage of Adverbs:&lt;/strong&gt;
        &lt;ul&gt;
                &lt;li&gt;Adverbs like &lt;strong&gt;&quot;consequently,&quot; &quot;therefore,&quot; and &quot;thus&quot;&lt;/strong&gt; are used to show cause-and-effect relationships.&lt;/li&gt;
                &lt;li&gt;Correct placement of adverbs ensures clarity and coherence in sentences.&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;/ul&gt;
        &lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Common Errors:&lt;/strong&gt;
        &lt;ul&gt;
                &lt;li&gt;Misspelling or incorrect usage of words can change the meaning or make the sentence grammatically incorrect.&lt;/li&gt;
                &lt;li&gt;Always cross-check the spelling and meaning of words in formal writing.&lt;/li&gt;
        &lt;/ul&gt;
        &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;option 1&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Lives &lt;/strong&gt;should be used here instead of&lt;strong&gt; live.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The given sentence is in present tense.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In &lt;strong&gt;simple present &lt;/strong&gt;tense, generally the &lt;strong&gt;base form of verb &lt;/strong&gt;is used. But in &lt;strong&gt;third person&lt;/strong&gt; singular V1+s/es form is used.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example&lt;/strong&gt;: My mother goes for a morning walk daily.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Sister-in-law is &lt;strong&gt;singular&lt;/strong&gt; and therefore, &lt;strong&gt;V1+s/es&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp; should be used.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus, the part that contains grammatical error is&lt;strong&gt; My sister-in-law who live&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The primary issue in the sentence is the incorrect use of the pronoun &amp;quot;their&amp;quot; to refer to the singular noun &amp;quot;South Korea.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct pronoun should be &amp;quot;its&amp;quot; to match the singular noun.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Thus, the error is located in &lt;strong&gt;part C&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;C&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;Since he was going to live in South Korea for some time, he thought he should learn something about its culture.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;A: &amp;quot;Since he was going to live in South Korea for some time,&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;B: &amp;quot;he thought he should&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;(B).&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error lies in&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Part (B)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the given sentence,&amp;nbsp;the use of the relative pronoun&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;who&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;is incorrect in this context.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The relative pronoun&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;who&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;should be used to refer to the subject of a sentence.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(0, 0, 0);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Example:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;The musician&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;who&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;wrote this song is Indian.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The relative pronoun&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;whom&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;should be used to refer to the object of a verb or preposition.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Example:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Whom&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;do you like best?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the use of the relative pronoun&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;who&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;in&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Part (B)&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;of the sentence&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;should be replaced by a relative pronoun&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;whom.&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;(B).&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;​&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Correct sentence&lt;/u&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;I do not know with&lt;strong&gt; whom&lt;/strong&gt; I will go to the prom.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;​&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;​​​&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;​&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Pronouns&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;are words that take the place of a noun.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Relative pronouns&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;are used at the beginning of an adjective clause (a dependent clause that modifies a noun).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The three most common relative pronouns are&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;who, which and that.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
		&lt;ul&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Who&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;has two other forms, the object form&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;whom&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;and the possessive form&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;whose&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Whose&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;can be used for people, animals or things:&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;That&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;and&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;which&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;are used to start two different types of adjective clauses called essential and non-essential clauses.&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;That&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;always indicates a clause that is essential to the meaning of the sentence because it defines or identifies the noun it refers to.
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Example:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Raima&amp;nbsp;wore the shoes&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;that&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;she bought in Jaipur.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;​​&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Which&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;may also be used to introduce an essential clause.
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Example:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Raima&amp;nbsp;wore the shoes&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;which&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;she bought in Jaipur.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Which&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is used in a non-essential clause modifying an animal or a thing.
			&lt;ul&gt;
				&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Example:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;&lt;s&gt;Raima&amp;nbsp;wore her best leather shoes,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;that&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;she bought in Jaipur.&lt;/s&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;[Incorrect]&lt;br /&gt;
				&lt;em&gt;Raima&amp;nbsp;wore her best leather shoes,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;which&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;she bought in Jaipur.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;[Correct]&lt;/li&gt;
			&lt;/ul&gt;
			&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;/ul&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;46px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/images/production/quesImages/quesImage292.png&quot; width=&quot;127px&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;त्रुटि वाक्य के &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Part (B&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;)&lt;/span&gt; में निहित है।&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;दिए गए वाक्य में relative pronoun&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;who&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;का प्रयोग इस सन्दर्भ में गलत है।&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;वाक्य के Subject&amp;nbsp;को संदर्भित करने के लिए&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;who&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;का उपयोग किया जाना चाहिए।
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(0, 0, 0);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Example:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;The musician&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;who&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;wrote this song is Indian.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Relative pronoun&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;whom&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;किसी क्रिया या पूर्वसर्ग की वस्तु को संदर्भित करने के लिए इस्तेमाल किया जाना चाहिए।
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Example:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Whom&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;do you like best?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;​इसलिए, वाक्य के&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Part (B)&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;में relative pronoun&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;who&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;के उपयोग को relative pronoun&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;whom&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;से प्रतिस्थापित किया जाना चाहिए।&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Option 4&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;#39;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The phrase &amp;quot;No sooner did we arrive&amp;quot; is a correct construction of the correlative conjunction &amp;quot;no sooner... than,&amp;quot; which is used to show that one event happens immediately after another.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;In the structure &amp;quot;No sooner did + subject + base verb,&amp;quot; the auxiliary verb &amp;quot;did&amp;quot; is used for the simple past tense, which is appropriate here to indicate that the arrival was followed quickly by another event.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;quot;No sooner did we arrive&amp;quot; fits grammatically, making it the correct choice in this context.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 4&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;No sooner did we arrive at the airport than we got busy with the luggage we were carrying.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 1: &amp;quot;No sooner arrived we&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This structure is incorrect because &amp;quot;arrived&amp;quot; is in the simple past tense and lacks the auxiliary verb &amp;quot;did&amp;quot; for the correct question form.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 2: &amp;quot;No sooner had we arrived&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This is a valid structure, but it uses the past perfect tense, which can work in a different context. However, in this case, the simple past tense with &amp;quot;did&amp;quot; is more appropriate for immediate actions.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Option 3: &amp;quot;No sooner we arrived&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This construction is incorrect because it lacks the auxiliary verb &amp;quot;did&amp;quot; in the appropriate form.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The primary issue in the sentence lies in the incorrect use of the preposition &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;with&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; after the verb &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;acquiesce&lt;/strong&gt;.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct preposition that follows &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;acquiesce&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;to&lt;/strong&gt;,&amp;quot; not &amp;quot;with.&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct phrase should be &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;acquiesce to&lt;/strong&gt; the orders of,&amp;quot; which means to agree or comply passively.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Thus, the error is located in &lt;strong&gt;part 3&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;The thieves had no alternative but to &lt;strong&gt;acquiesce to&lt;/strong&gt; the orders of the police.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;  line-height: 1.38;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;The erroneous part is &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;option 3) i.e. &amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;you would come&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;  line-height: 1.38;&quot;&gt;&lt;span id=&quot;docs-internal-guid-8f3d6a48-7fff-3afb-71de-f8e586c1c4df&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;  line-height: 1.38;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;The error lies in part &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span id=&quot;docs-internal-guid-8f3d6a48-7fff-3afb-71de-f8e586c1c4df&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;you would come&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;In the given sentence, the action &amp;#39;surprise party&amp;#39; took place &amp;#39;last week&amp;#39;, which implies that the action took place in the past.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;According to the rules of conditional sentences, when an action takes place in the past, and we regret it, then &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;Wish + Past Perfect&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;structure is used.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;I wish you would come&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt; should be used when an incident is occurring in the present.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;Whereas&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;I wish you had come&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;is used to indicate a wish for something that has already happened in the past.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;Therefore i&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;n the given sentence, we need to &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;use &amp;#39;had&amp;#39; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;in place of&lt;span style=&quot;font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt; &amp;#39;would&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;to make the sentence grammatically correct.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span id=&quot;docs-internal-guid-8f3d6a48-7fff-3afb-71de-f8e586c1c4df&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;Hence, &lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;the correct answer is option&amp;nbsp;3.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;  line-height: 1.38;&quot;&gt;&lt;span id=&quot;docs-internal-guid-8f3d6a48-7fff-3afb-71de-f8e586c1c4df&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;  line-height: 1.38;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span id=&quot;docs-internal-guid-8f3d6a48-7fff-3afb-71de-f8e586c1c4df&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;Correct sentence&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/u&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;Last week&amp;rsquo;s surprise party was terrific. I wish&lt;strong&gt; you had come.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;Option 2&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the second part of the given sentence, the singular form of the verb &amp;#39;lead&amp;#39; is incorrect.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The subject &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;Each of these&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; is singular and requires a singular verb.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;each&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;is used as a subject, it always takes a singular verb.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the correct verb form should be&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;leads&amp;#39; &lt;/strong&gt;instead of&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;lead&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Hence, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;option 2&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Correct sentence:&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Each of these three roads leads to the railway station&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The first part (I) &amp;#39;Each of these&amp;#39; is correct and does not contain any errors.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The third part (III) &amp;#39;to the railway station&amp;#39; is grammatically correct and does not contain any errors.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Arun never shirked away&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;i.e. this part of the sentence&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;has an error&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In the given sentence, the use of the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;past tense form of the verb&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;shirked&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;incorrect&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The given sentence is in the &lt;strong&gt;simple present tense&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;as it is used &lt;strong&gt;to describe habits, unchanging situations, general truths, and fixed arrangements&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;third-person singular present verb &amp;#39;shirks&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;should be used&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;in place of&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;the&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;past tense form of the verb&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;shirked&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;option 3&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Always on the lookout for opportunities, &lt;strong&gt;Arun never shirks away&lt;/strong&gt; from new assignments&lt;/em&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

The correct answer is: &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;and neither side were willing to&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The conjunction&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;neither&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; is always followed by a &lt;strong&gt;singular verb&lt;/strong&gt;.

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For example: &lt;strong&gt;Neither &lt;/strong&gt;side of the field &lt;strong&gt;is&lt;/strong&gt; visible.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Similarly, in this context,&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;neither side&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; should be followed by the&amp;nbsp;singular verb &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;was&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; instead of &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;were&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The correct sentence should be &amp;quot;&lt;em&gt;...and neither side was willing to compromise on the compensation amount to be given.&lt;/em&gt;&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;option 1&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;(c).&amp;#39;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error lies in&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;(c)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;part&amp;nbsp;of the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In this sentence, the subject is&lt;b&gt; &amp;quot;he&amp;quot; &lt;/b&gt;and the object is&lt;b&gt; &amp;quot;myself and him.&amp;quot;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;b&gt;&amp;quot;Myself&amp;quot; &lt;/b&gt;can be used as the object only when the subject is&lt;b&gt; &amp;quot;I.&amp;quot;&lt;/b&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example&lt;/strong&gt;:&lt;em&gt; I want this book for &lt;strong&gt;myself&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, the use of&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;myself&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;should be replaced by&lt;strong&gt; &amp;#39;m&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;e&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;to make it grammatically correct&lt;em&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;​​&lt;/em&gt;&lt;u&gt;Correct sentence&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;He is trying&amp;nbsp;to earn money for &lt;strong&gt;me&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;and him&lt;/em&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;present tense&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;is the base form of the verb.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;We use&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;do&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;and&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;does&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;to make questions with the present simple.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;We use&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;does&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;for the&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;third person singular (she/he/it)&lt;/em&gt;&amp;nbsp;and&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;do&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;for the others.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;We use do and does with question words like&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;where, what&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;and&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;when.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Example:&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Where do Angela and Rita live?&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;em style=&quot;color: rgb(0, 0, 0);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/hinglish-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Hinglish&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul style=&quot;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;त्रुटि वाक्य के भाग&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;(c)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;में है।&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;इस वाक्य में, subject &amp;quot;he&amp;quot;&amp;nbsp;है और &lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;object,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;&amp;quot;myself and him&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt; है।&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;&amp;quot;Myself&amp;quot;&lt;/span&gt; का प्रयोग object के रूप में तभी किया जा सकता है जब&lt;strong&gt; subject&amp;nbsp;&amp;quot;I&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;हो।
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Example&lt;/span&gt;:&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;I want this book for&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;myself&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;इसलिए वाक्य के&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;myself&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;प्रयोग को&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;me&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;से बदल देना चाहिए ताकि वह व्याकरण की दृष्टि से सही हो।​&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &amp;#39;&lt;strong&gt;Option 2&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;time reference&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;#39;Early, during December 2021&amp;#39; is &lt;strong&gt;incorrect. &lt;/strong&gt;It doesn&amp;#39;t properly specify when the appointment happened.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Rather than saying &amp;#39;Early, during December 2021,&amp;#39; it would be correct to say &amp;#39;early in December 2021&amp;#39; or &amp;#39;during December 2021.&amp;#39; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The word &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;early&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;doesn&amp;#39;t &lt;/strong&gt;need the &lt;strong&gt;accompaniment&lt;/strong&gt; of &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;during.&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the &lt;strong&gt;correct segment &lt;/strong&gt;should be &lt;em&gt;&amp;#39;Early in December 2021&amp;#39; or &amp;#39;In early December 2021&amp;#39;, which clearly represents the period at the beginning of December.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is: &lt;strong&gt;c&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correlative Conjunctions&lt;/strong&gt; are always found in pair.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;else&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; and &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;but&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; are correlative conjunctions i.e.,&amp;nbsp;they are always used in &lt;strong&gt;pair&lt;/strong&gt;.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;For example:&amp;nbsp;It was nothing &lt;strong&gt;else but &lt;/strong&gt;an attempt of secession or divorce within the Federation.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Similarly, in this question, &amp;#39;nothing else&amp;#39; must be followed by &amp;#39;but&amp;#39;, not &amp;#39;than&amp;#39;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence, &amp;#39;than&amp;#39; must be replaced by &amp;#39;but&amp;#39; to make the sentence grammatically correct.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is:&amp;nbsp;​&lt;em&gt;An intelligent&amp;nbsp;person&amp;nbsp;is defrauding&amp;nbsp;himself of the greatness in life that might be his if he watches&amp;nbsp;nothing else &lt;strong&gt;but&lt;/strong&gt; soap operas and&amp;nbsp;derogatory movies.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;Some of the important Correlative Conjunctions are:

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Either&amp;hellip;.or&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Neither&amp;hellip;.nor&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Hardly&amp;hellip;.when&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Scarcely&amp;hellip;.when&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Both&amp;hellip;and&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;If&amp;hellip;then&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Not only&amp;hellip;.but also&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Rather&amp;hellip;.than&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Whether&amp;hellip;or&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;No sooner&amp;hellip;than&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Else&amp;hellip;but&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Lest&amp;hellip;should&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Other&amp;hellip;than&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;So&amp;hellip;that&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

