questions.explanation:
&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 4&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The sentence &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;I want to buy some books so today I must go to the market.&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is grammatically correct.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Each part of the sentence has been checked for grammatical correctness.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;There are no errors in any part of the sentence.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;No Error (Option 4)&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;I want to buy some books so today I must go to the market.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Part 1: &amp;quot;I want to buy some books&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Part 2: &amp;quot;so today I must go&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Part 3: &amp;quot;to the market.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; This part of the sentence is grammatically correct and does not require any changes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The expression &amp;quot;in the press&amp;quot; is correct, but &amp;quot;and the platform&amp;quot; should be &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;and on the platform.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The correct preposition to use with&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;platform&amp;quot; in this context is &amp;quot;on.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;The phrase should be &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;in the press and on the platform&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; to maintain parallelism and proper prepositional usage.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;Option 3&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;div&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct Sentence:&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;em&gt;&amp;quot;The matter has been discussed both in the press and &lt;strong&gt;on&lt;/strong&gt; the platform.&amp;quot;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is:&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;When Mayank came&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error in the original sentence is in the &lt;strong&gt;verb tense agreement&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The issue is that the past tense &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;came&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; in this segment conflicts with the use of the future tense &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;shall go&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; in the following segment.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In this case, &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;comes&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; is appropriate.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This suggests that whenever &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Mayank comes&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; as a regular occurrence or in the future.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In conditional statements, especially those &lt;strong&gt;expressing future conditions&lt;/strong&gt;, use &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;comes&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; in the &lt;strong&gt;if-clause&lt;/strong&gt; to indicate a possible future event.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So, the &lt;strong&gt;correct sentence&lt;/strong&gt; would be:&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;When Mayank comes, I shall go with him to the circus.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thus, &lt;strong&gt;option 2&lt;/strong&gt; is the correct answer.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;C&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error lies in&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Part C&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;Little&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; has a negative meaning and it is used to&amp;nbsp;mean &lt;strong&gt;&amp;lsquo;not, as much as, maybe, expected or wished for&amp;rsquo;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;A little&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt; is a&amp;nbsp;quantifier meaning&lt;strong&gt; &amp;lsquo;some&amp;rsquo; &lt;/strong&gt;and it is used with &lt;em&gt;singular uncountable nouns&lt;/em&gt;.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example&lt;/strong&gt;:&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Mary said nothing, but she drank some tea and ate &lt;strong&gt;a little&lt;/strong&gt; bread.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;little&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;present in&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Part C&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;of the sentence&amp;nbsp;should be replaced by&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;a little&amp;#39; &lt;/span&gt;or&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;some&amp;#39;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;to make it grammatically correct.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence, the correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;#39;C&amp;#39;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Correct sentence&lt;/u&gt;:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;em&gt;&amp;nbsp;As John had taken only a few sips of tea there was still &lt;strong&gt;a little (some)&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;tea left in the cup.&lt;span id=&quot;docs-internal-guid-97fb2992-7fff-1056-ed48-066455c8747e&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;background-color: transparent; font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;border: none; display: inline-block; overflow: hidden; width: 25px; height: 25px;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;25&quot; src=&quot;https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/UckobJCVter23fGp7NEUDWH51cuUtQ2Zwf-TscS883iKoQdwCoGdpRuAIHjZywZi-oNY0ev4INnI8D4oPykSBHStY-lpyl0EYEUFBj_cAXiB7EAsDIlidvn7XlwIsOevtnTVhpYd&quot; style=&quot;margin-left: 0px; margin-top: 0px;&quot; width=&quot;25&quot; /&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;​&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;​​​&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;​&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;We use &lt;strong&gt;quantifiers&lt;/strong&gt; when we want to give someone information about the number of something: &lt;em&gt;how much or how many&lt;/em&gt;.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Sometimes we use a quantifier in the place of a &lt;strong&gt;determiner&lt;/strong&gt;.
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;Most &lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;children start school at the age of five.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;​​&lt;/strong&gt;We can use these quantifiers &lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;with both countable and uncountable nouns.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Example:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;There was a lot of food but &lt;strong&gt;no&lt;/strong&gt; drinks.&amp;nbsp;&lt;br /&gt;
		&amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp; &amp;nbsp;Joe has &lt;strong&gt;lots&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;strong&gt;of&lt;/strong&gt; friends.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;Karan call the restaurant&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The phrase&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;if he could&amp;quot; &lt;/strong&gt;portrays a situation that happened in the past. &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;Called&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; is correct.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The verb &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;call&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; should be in the past tense, so it should be&lt;strong&gt; &amp;quot;Karan called the restaurant&amp;quot;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;To ask if he could&amp;quot; and &amp;quot;reserve a table for tomorrow&amp;quot; are grammatically correct.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Thus, the correct sentence would be: Karan called the restaurant to ask if he could reserve a table for the next day.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, &lt;strong&gt;the correct answer is option 1&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Correct sentence:&amp;nbsp;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;Karan &lt;strong&gt;called&lt;/strong&gt; the restaurant to ask if he could reserve a table for the next day.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/confusion-points-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Confusion Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If it is written as &amp;quot;Karan call&lt;strong&gt;s&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;, we can change the later part.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;option 1&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error in the sentence is in the segment &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;on where common&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The sentence is intended to express that research has mixed results on how common a symptom digestive problems are in relation to infections.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The adjective &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;common&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; needs to directly modify the noun it describes, which is &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;symptom&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So,&amp;nbsp;replace&amp;nbsp;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;where&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; with &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;how&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot; and place&amp;nbsp;&amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;common&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;&amp;nbsp;directly before &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;symptom&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;. This makes sense because the question is about the degree of commonality (hence &amp;quot;how common&amp;quot;), not the location (which would be signified by &amp;quot;where&amp;quot;).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In conclusion, the segment that contains the error is &amp;quot;&lt;strong&gt;on where common&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;quot;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, option 1 is correct.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Correct sentence:&amp;nbsp;&amp;quot;Digestive problems have been increasingly linked to the infections, but research is mixed &lt;strong&gt;on how common&lt;/strong&gt; a symptom it is.&amp;quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;option 1&amp;nbsp;i.e. A.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The error lies in&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;the wrong usage of the pronoun&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;&amp;lsquo;I&amp;rsquo;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;in Part B.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;I&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; will be replaced with &lt;strong&gt;&amp;quot;me&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt; i.e.&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;objective&amp;nbsp;case&lt;/strong&gt; of the pronoun.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Whenever any &lt;strong&gt;conjunction&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;is used in a sentence, we will always use &lt;strong&gt;objective&amp;nbsp;case after it.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Hence, error lies in &lt;strong&gt;part A&lt;/strong&gt; of the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

